1
00:00:00,960 --> 00:00:02,880
(THUNDER CRASHING, WIND HOWLING)

2
00:00:12,920 --> 00:00:14,360
-How are we looking?
-Oh!

3
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:17,280
-About ready, I think.
-Hmm.

4
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:22,400
Any thoughts on the, uh, interference?

5
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:25,280
Um, a stray FM broadcast, possibly,

6
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:29,560
but I've fitted some ferrite suppressors
and some RF chokes.

7
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:30,680
Just in case.

8
00:00:36,440 --> 00:00:37,680
Are you sure you want to
go through with this?

9
00:00:37,760 --> 00:00:41,440
-I mean, the last time it was very...
-But she's so lonely.

10
00:00:43,160 --> 00:00:44,680
Excellent, then.

11
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:46,800
Excellent.

12
00:00:52,480 --> 00:00:53,680
(FEEDBACK)

13
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:57,840
Caliburn House, night four,

14
00:00:57,920 --> 00:01:00,680
November 25th, 1974,

15
00:01:01,240 --> 00:01:02,840
11:04 p.m.

16
00:01:05,760 --> 00:01:06,880
(THUNDER CRACKING)

17
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:14,120
I'm talking to the spirit
that inhabits this house.

18
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:17,160
-Are you there?
-(STATIC)

19
00:01:17,240 --> 00:01:18,520
Can you hear me?

20
00:01:23,480 --> 00:01:27,080
I'm speaking to the lost soul
that abides in this place.

21
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:29,400
(CLANKING)

22
00:01:29,480 --> 00:01:30,920
(FEEDBACK)

23
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:34,280
Come to me. Speak to me.

24
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:37,120
Let me show you the way home.

25
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:39,840
(GROANING, FEEDBACK INTENSIFYING)

26
00:01:41,080 --> 00:01:42,120
(DISTANT MOANING)

27
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:44,320
Let me show you the way home!

28
00:01:50,680 --> 00:01:52,720
(GASPING)

29
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:55,040
(INHALES SHARPLY)

30
00:01:57,320 --> 00:01:59,160
-Emma?
-(WHEEZING)

31
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:02,080
-She's so...
-So0...so what?

32
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:04,640
Dead.

33
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:07,600
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

34
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:22,720
Boo! (LAUGHS)

35
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:24,480
Hello. I'm looking for a ghost.

36
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:25,640
And you are?

37
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:27,560
Ghostbusters.

38
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:29,560
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

39
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:03,000
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

40
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:05,680
-I'm The Doctor.
-Doctor what?

41
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:07,360
If you like, and this is Clara.

42
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:11,960
Ah, but you are very different.

43
00:03:12,040 --> 00:03:14,920
Ha! You are Major Alec Palmer,

44
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:16,760
member of the Baker Street Irregulars,

45
00:03:16,840 --> 00:03:18,880
the Ministry of Ungentlemanly Warfare,

46
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:21,640
specialise in espionage, sabotage

47
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:23,480
and reconnaissance behind enemy lines.

48
00:03:23,560 --> 00:03:25,680
You're a talented watercolourist,

49
00:03:25,760 --> 00:03:28,440
professor of psychology and...

50
00:03:28,520 --> 00:03:29,800
ghost hunter.

51
00:03:31,040 --> 00:03:32,600
Total pleasure.

52
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:34,600
-Massive.
-Actually, you're wrong.

53
00:03:34,720 --> 00:03:37,240
Professor Palmer spent
most of the war as a POW.

54
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:39,280
Actually, that's a lie
told by a very brave man

55
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:40,920
involved in very secret operations.

56
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:42,320
The type of man
who keeps a Victoria Cross

57
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:43,840
in a box in the attic, eh?

58
00:03:43,920 --> 00:03:46,440
But you know that
because you're Emma Grayling.

59
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:50,320
-The professor's companion.
-Assistant.

60
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:51,760
It's 1974.

61
00:03:51,840 --> 00:03:54,840
You're the assistant and
"non-objective equipment"”.

62
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:57,520
-Meaning psychic.
-Getting that. Bless you, though.

63
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:00,000
Relax, Emma. He's military intelligence.

64
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:02,760
-So, what is all this in aid of?
-Health & Safety.

65
00:04:03,440 --> 00:04:07,440
Yeah. The Ministry got wind
of what's going on down here,

66
00:04:07,960 --> 00:04:09,920
sent me to check that
everything's in order.

67
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,040
They don't have the right.

68
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:12,880
Don't worry, governor,
I'll be out of here in five minutes.

69
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:14,800
Oh! Oh, look!

70
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:18,440
Oh, lovely, the ACR99821.

71
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:21,200
Oh, bliss. Nice action
on the toggle switches.

72
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:24,040
You know, I do love a toggle switch.

73
00:04:24,120 --> 00:04:27,400
Actually, I like the word "toggle".
(CHUCKLES)

74
00:04:27,480 --> 00:04:29,320
Nice noun. Excellent verb.

75
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:31,360
Oi, don't mess with the settings.

76
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:34,120
-(BUZZING)
-What's that?

77
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:36,720
Gadget. Health & Safety.
Classified, I'm afraid.

78
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:39,760
You know, while the backroom boffins
work out a few kinks.

79
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:41,760
EMMA: What's it telling you?

80
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:44,120
It's telling me that
you haven't been exposed to

81
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:46,560
any life-threatening
transmundane emanations.

82
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:48,800
So...

83
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:52,320
-where's the ghost? Huh?
-(THUNDER RUMBLING)

84
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:57,320
Show me the ghost.

85
00:04:57,920 --> 00:04:59,440
(THUDDING)

86
00:05:01,240 --> 00:05:02,440
It's ghost time.

87
00:05:05,440 --> 00:05:08,000
ALEC: I will not have this stolen out
from under me, do you understand?

88
00:05:08,080 --> 00:05:09,720
Um... No, not really. Sorry.

89
00:05:09,800 --> 00:05:12,800
I will not have my work stolen
and be fobbed off with a pat on the back

90
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:14,760
and a letter from the Queen.
Never again.

91
00:05:14,840 --> 00:05:17,040
This is my house, Doctor,
and it belongs to me.

92
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:20,440
-Is this actually your house?
-It is.

93
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:23,840
(CHUCKLES) Sorry.
You went to the bank and said,

94
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:26,280
"You know that gigantic,
old haunted house on the moors?

95
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:28,280
"The one that dossers are
too scared to doss in,

96
00:05:28,360 --> 00:05:30,400
"the one that birds are
too scared to fly over?”

97
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:33,480
And then you said, "I'd like to
buy it, please, with my money"?

98
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:35,200
Yes, I did, actually.

99
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:37,440
-That's incredibly brave.
-(DOOR CREAKS)

100
00:05:37,520 --> 00:05:39,320
(GASPS)

101
00:05:39,400 --> 00:05:40,640
Listen, Major.

102
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:43,600
We just need to know
what's going on here.

103
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:46,240
-For the Ministry?
-You know I can't answer that.

104
00:05:47,480 --> 00:05:48,680
(SIGHS)

105
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:51,040
Very well.

106
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,160
Follow me.

107
00:06:01,920 --> 00:06:04,240
So what's an empathic psychic?

108
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:07,880
Sometimes I sense feelings,

109
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:09,960
the way a telepath can sense thoughts.

110
00:06:10,040 --> 00:06:12,040
Sometimes, though, not always.

111
00:06:12,120 --> 00:06:16,080
The most compassionate people
you will ever meet, empathics.

112
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:17,480
And the loneliest.

113
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:20,400
I mean, exposing themselves
to all those hidden feelings,

114
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:22,520
all that guilt,

115
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,120
pain and sorrow and...

116
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:25,240
-Doctor.
-Yes.

117
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:26,360
Shh!

118
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:29,360
Do you, uh, care to have a look?

119
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:36,040
Caliburn House is over 400 years old,

120
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,160
but she has been around much longer.

121
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,160
The Caliburn Gast.

122
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:47,560
She's mentioned in local Saxon poetry

123
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:49,200
and parish folk tales.

124
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:51,160
The Wraith of the Lady.

125
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:52,800
The Maiden in the Dark.

126
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:55,680
The Witch of the Well.

127
00:06:57,720 --> 00:06:58,960
Is she real?

128
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:00,720
As in actually real?

129
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:02,320
ALEC: Oh, she's real.

130
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:05,080
In the 17th century,
a local clergyman saw her.

131
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:07,840
He wrote that,
"Her presence was accompanied by

132
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:09,480
"a dreadful knocking,

133
00:07:09,560 --> 00:07:12,160
"as if the Devil himself
demanded entry".

134
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:16,760
During the war,
American airmen stationed here

135
00:07:16,840 --> 00:07:18,760
left offerings of tinned Spam.

136
00:07:18,840 --> 00:07:22,520
The tins were found in 1965
bricked up in the servants' pantry,

137
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:24,400
along with a number
of handwritten notes,

138
00:07:24,480 --> 00:07:25,840
appeals to the Gast.

139
00:07:26,920 --> 00:07:29,160
"For the love of God,

140
00:07:29,240 --> 00:07:30,920
"stop screaming.”

141
00:07:34,160 --> 00:07:36,000
She never changes.

142
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:39,680
The angle's different,
the framing, but she's

143
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:42,560
always in exactly the same position.
Why is that?

144
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:43,760
We don't know.

145
00:07:44,200 --> 00:07:46,280
She's an objective phenomenon.

146
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:48,680
But objective recording equipment
can't detect her.

147
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:50,760
Without the presence of
a powerful psychic.

148
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:53,160
Absolutely.

149
00:07:53,240 --> 00:07:54,520
Very well done.

150
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,240
(GASPING) She knows I'm here.

151
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:02,640
I can feel her

152
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:06,200
calling out to me.

153
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:08,880
What is she saying?

154
00:08:10,600 --> 00:08:12,920
"Help me."

155
00:08:22,640 --> 00:08:24,520
DOCTOR: The Witch of the Well.

156
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:28,400
So, where is the well?

157
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:31,760
A copy of the oldest plan
that we could find.

158
00:08:32,440 --> 00:08:35,160
There is no well on the property.

159
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:36,760
None that we could find, anyway.

160
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,120
(GASPING)

161
00:08:42,520 --> 00:08:44,000
-(WHISPERS) You coming?
-Where?

162
00:08:44,080 --> 00:08:45,960
-To find the ghost.
-Why would I want to do that?

163
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:47,200
Because you want to. Come on.

164
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:49,600
-Well, I dispute that assertion.
-Eh?

165
00:08:53,560 --> 00:08:55,520
I'm giving you a face.

166
00:08:55,680 --> 00:08:56,960
Here. Can you see me?

167
00:08:57,040 --> 00:08:58,320
Look at my face.

168
00:08:58,880 --> 00:09:00,720
(GRUMBLING) Fine.

169
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:07,480
Dare me.

170
00:09:07,560 --> 00:09:10,040
I dare you. No takesie-backsies?

171
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:18,960
The music room is
the heart of the house.

172
00:09:31,160 --> 00:09:34,000
Say we actually find her.
What do we say?

173
00:09:34,080 --> 00:09:38,360
We ask her how she came to be
or if she is.

174
00:09:38,440 --> 00:09:40,080
-Why?
-Because I don't know.

175
00:09:40,160 --> 00:09:42,120
And ignorance is, um,

176
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:43,760
what's the opposite of bliss?

177
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:46,400
-Carlisle?
-Yes.

178
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:49,160
Yes, Carlisle. Ignorance is Carlisle.

179
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:27,480
Is he really from the Ministry?

180
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:29,720
Uh, I don't know.

181
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,360
He's certainly got the right demeanour.

182
00:10:33,440 --> 00:10:35,800
Capricious, brilliant.

183
00:10:37,440 --> 00:10:40,160
-Deceitful.
-Yes. (CHUCKLES)

184
00:10:41,040 --> 00:10:42,440
He's a liar.

185
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:46,600
But you know,
that's often the way that it is

186
00:10:48,240 --> 00:10:51,400
when someone's seen a thing or two.

187
00:10:52,520 --> 00:10:54,560
Experience makes liars of us all.

188
00:10:55,080 --> 00:10:56,640
We lie about who we are,

189
00:10:58,280 --> 00:11:00,120
about what we've done...

190
00:11:00,200 --> 00:11:01,920
And how we feel?

191
00:11:04,880 --> 00:11:05,920
Yes.

192
00:11:06,720 --> 00:11:07,880
Always.

193
00:11:08,560 --> 00:11:09,800
Always that.

194
00:11:14,280 --> 00:11:16,040
You know, I have to, um...

195
00:11:16,120 --> 00:11:17,840
I have to be getting on with things.

196
00:11:17,920 --> 00:11:19,160
The, um...

197
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:21,960
-The equipment and so forth.
-Of course.

198
00:11:29,040 --> 00:11:30,480
DOCTOR: Ah, the music room.

199
00:11:31,120 --> 00:11:32,920
The heart of the house.

200
00:11:35,160 --> 00:11:36,400
Do you feel anything?

201
00:11:37,560 --> 00:11:39,840
-No.
-Your pants are so on fire.

202
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:41,240
(CLARA LAUGHING)

203
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:43,720
(BLOWING)

204
00:11:44,200 --> 00:11:45,600
(BUZZING)

205
00:11:49,120 --> 00:11:51,040
(WHISPERING) Do you feel like
you're being watched?

206
00:11:52,120 --> 00:11:53,400
What does being watched feel like?

207
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:56,240
Is it that funny tickly feeling
on the back of your neck?

208
00:11:56,320 --> 00:11:58,000
-That's the chap.
-Then, yes, a bit.

209
00:11:58,600 --> 00:12:00,920
Well, quite a big bit.

210
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:02,800
(THUNDER CRACKING)

211
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:08,080
(FLOOR CREAKING)

212
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:09,440
(GASPS)

213
00:12:12,160 --> 00:12:13,440
(SIGHS)

214
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:16,920
(CREAKING)

215
00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:19,640
I think she's here.

216
00:12:20,360 --> 00:12:21,600
(EXHALES)

217
00:12:23,880 --> 00:12:25,120
Cold spot.

218
00:12:25,520 --> 00:12:26,720
Spooky.

219
00:12:27,640 --> 00:12:29,000
Cold.

220
00:12:29,080 --> 00:12:30,320
Warm.

221
00:12:30,400 --> 00:12:32,920
Cold. Warm.

222
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,680
Cold. Warm. Cold.

223
00:12:35,760 --> 00:12:38,040
-Warm. Cold.
-(METALLIC CLICKING)

224
00:12:41,800 --> 00:12:43,000
Doctor?

225
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:46,840
-Doctor!
-What?

226
00:12:47,920 --> 00:12:49,400
I'm not happy.

227
00:12:50,640 --> 00:12:51,800
No.

228
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:56,760
(DOOR CREAKS)

229
00:12:57,560 --> 00:12:58,720
Hey!

230
00:13:17,880 --> 00:13:19,600
-(THUDDING)
-Oh...

231
00:13:21,440 --> 00:13:22,480
What was that?

232
00:13:22,560 --> 00:13:24,320
(THUDDING)

233
00:13:26,760 --> 00:13:28,040
(BOTH GASPING)

234
00:13:33,520 --> 00:13:34,800
Does it seem colder?

235
00:13:41,120 --> 00:13:42,320
(COUGHS)

236
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:46,720
(THUDDING)

237
00:13:47,840 --> 00:13:49,080
She's coming.

238
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:52,880
(THUDDING)

239
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:55,760
Okay. What is that?

240
00:13:55,840 --> 00:13:58,440
It's, uh, it's a very loud noise.

241
00:13:58,520 --> 00:14:01,920
It's a very loud, very angry noise.

242
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,120
-What's making it?
-I don't know. Are you making it?

243
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:06,560
-(THUDDING CONTINUES)
-(YELPS)

244
00:14:08,640 --> 00:14:09,920
-Doctor?
-Yes.

245
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,240
-I may be a teeny, tiny bit terrified.
-Yes?

246
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:14,800
-But I'm still a grown-up.
-Mainly. Yes, and...

247
00:14:14,880 --> 00:14:17,760
There's no need to
actually hold my hand.

248
00:14:17,840 --> 00:14:19,320
-Clara?
-Yeah.

249
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:20,680
I'm not holding your hand.

250
00:14:23,160 --> 00:14:24,640
(BOTH SCREAMING)

251
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:30,360
Oh!

252
00:14:33,120 --> 00:14:35,120
-Has this happened before?
-Never.

253
00:14:35,200 --> 00:14:37,240
Ah! Camera. Camera!

254
00:14:42,520 --> 00:14:43,760
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

255
00:14:49,680 --> 00:14:51,520
(WAILING)

256
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:57,400
(GASPING) Doctor!

257
00:14:58,600 --> 00:14:59,800
(SCREAMING)

258
00:15:02,240 --> 00:15:04,240
-GHOST: Help me!
-Oh!

259
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:05,680
(CRASHING)

260
00:15:06,960 --> 00:15:08,920
CLARA: Doctor.

261
00:15:36,560 --> 00:15:37,640
Oh!

262
00:15:38,960 --> 00:15:41,120
I'd rather have a nice cup of tea.

263
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:43,240
Me, too.

264
00:15:43,320 --> 00:15:46,080
Whisky is the eleventh
most disgusting thing ever invented.

265
00:15:47,960 --> 00:15:49,760
(SIGHS)

266
00:15:50,160 --> 00:15:54,040
I had a little peek at your records
back at the Ministry.

267
00:15:54,760 --> 00:15:57,000
Well, you've certainly seen
a thing or two in your time.

268
00:15:57,080 --> 00:16:00,160
Disrupting U-boat operations
across the North Sea.

269
00:16:00,240 --> 00:16:02,800
Sabotaging railway lines across Europe.

270
00:16:02,880 --> 00:16:04,480
Operation Gibbon.

271
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:06,840
The one with
the carrier pigeon"s brilliant.

272
00:16:07,480 --> 00:16:08,720
I do love a carrier pigeon.

273
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:13,320
I did my duty
but then so did thousands of others.

274
00:16:13,400 --> 00:16:15,640
Millions of others.

275
00:16:16,680 --> 00:16:18,160
I was just lucky enough to come back.

276
00:16:18,240 --> 00:16:22,000
Yes, but how does that man,
that war hero, end up here,

277
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:24,520
in a lonely old house
looking for ghosts?

278
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:32,360
Because I killed.
And I caused to have killed.

279
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:37,920
I sent young men and women
to their deaths.

280
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:41,680
(INHALES DEEPLY)
But here I am, still alive and...

281
00:16:43,120 --> 00:16:45,520
But it does tend to haunt you,

282
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:47,520
living, after so much of...

283
00:16:48,760 --> 00:16:51,000
the other thing.

284
00:16:51,400 --> 00:16:55,600
So, you and Professor Palmer,
have you ever...

285
00:16:56,280 --> 00:16:58,080
-You know.
-(SIGHS) No.

286
00:16:59,040 --> 00:17:00,400
Why not?

287
00:17:00,480 --> 00:17:02,040
You do know how he feels
about you, don't you?

288
00:17:02,120 --> 00:17:03,640
You of all people.

289
00:17:04,120 --> 00:17:05,880
(SIGHS) I don't know.

290
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:08,360
People like me,

291
00:17:09,440 --> 00:17:11,800
sometimes we get our signals mixed up.

292
00:17:11,880 --> 00:17:14,880
We think people are feeling
the way we want them to feel.

293
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:19,240
You know, when they're special to us.

294
00:17:20,800 --> 00:17:23,520
When really, there's nothing there.

295
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:25,560
Oh, this is there.

296
00:17:26,280 --> 00:17:28,560
-How do you know?
-Because it's obvious.

297
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:31,400
It sticks out, like a big chin.

298
00:17:33,800 --> 00:17:36,960
You see, I was alone and unmarried and

299
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:38,920
you know, I didn't mind dying.

300
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:42,160
I mean, not for that cause.
It was a very, very fine cause.

301
00:17:43,080 --> 00:17:45,160
Defeating the enemy.

302
00:17:45,840 --> 00:17:49,920
And if you could contact them,
what would you say?

303
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:52,360
Well, I'd very much like to thank them.

304
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:53,560
Ah.

305
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:57,720
Ping.

306
00:17:59,440 --> 00:18:00,680
What do you think she is?

307
00:18:03,360 --> 00:18:04,880
Not what I thought she'd be.

308
00:18:04,960 --> 00:18:08,000
-What did you think she'd be?
-Fun.

309
00:18:08,800 --> 00:18:10,280
Can I borrow your camera?

310
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:12,800
Ta.

311
00:18:14,360 --> 00:18:16,640
What about you and The Doctor?

312
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:19,360
Oh. Don't think so.

313
00:18:19,440 --> 00:18:22,000
-Good.
-Sorry?

314
00:18:22,840 --> 00:18:24,280
Don't trust him.

315
00:18:25,240 --> 00:18:27,320
There's a sliver of ice in his heart.

316
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:30,200
DOCTOR: Clara!

317
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:44,080
I've got this weird feeling
it's looking at me.

318
00:18:45,240 --> 00:18:46,400
It doesn't like me.

319
00:18:46,480 --> 00:18:48,520
The Tardis is like a cat.

320
00:18:48,760 --> 00:18:51,920
A bit slow to trust
but you'll get there in the end.

321
00:18:58,920 --> 00:19:00,000
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

322
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:05,360
Hey!

323
00:19:10,840 --> 00:19:12,120
You need a place to keep this.

324
00:19:12,360 --> 00:19:13,440
I've got one.

325
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:17,800
Or I had one. I think I had one.

326
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:20,080
Look around. See if you can find it.

327
00:19:20,920 --> 00:19:23,480
Did I have one? Am I going mad?

328
00:19:24,040 --> 00:19:26,280
No, not in here!

329
00:19:26,520 --> 00:19:30,080
How do you expect her to like you
if she's soaking wet?

330
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:31,960
It's a Health & Safety nightmare.

331
00:19:34,080 --> 00:19:35,200
Sorry.

332
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:36,640
(ELECTRONIC RUMBLING)

333
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:39,360
So, where are we going?

334
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:41,480
Nowhere. We're staying right here.

335
00:19:41,560 --> 00:19:44,960
Right here, on this exact spot,
if I can work out how to do it.

336
00:19:45,040 --> 00:19:46,480
So, when are we going?

337
00:19:47,200 --> 00:19:49,240
(LAUGHING) Oh, that is good.

338
00:19:49,560 --> 00:19:50,640
That is top-notch.

339
00:19:50,720 --> 00:19:52,400
-And the answer is?
-We're going always.

340
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:54,960
-We're going always.
-Totally.

341
00:19:55,120 --> 00:19:56,520
That's not actually a sentence.

342
00:19:56,600 --> 00:19:58,000
Well, it's got a verb in it.

343
00:19:58,200 --> 00:19:59,280
What do you think?

344
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:01,800
Uh, colour's a bit boisterous.

345
00:20:01,880 --> 00:20:03,440
I think it brings out my eyes.

346
00:20:03,520 --> 00:20:05,680
Makes my eyes hurt.

347
00:20:06,880 --> 00:20:09,160
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

348
00:20:11,600 --> 00:20:14,240
Did you... Did you see where he went?

349
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:16,760
I could hear an engine
but I can't see any lights.

350
00:20:32,520 --> 00:20:33,560
(GASPING)

351
00:20:33,640 --> 00:20:36,240
Back off! Hot suit! Hot, hot, hot!

352
00:20:36,440 --> 00:20:37,880
When are we?

353
00:20:37,960 --> 00:20:41,640
About six billion years ago.
It's a Tuesday, I think.

354
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:52,680
Hmm?

355
00:20:54,160 --> 00:20:55,480
(WHOOSHING)

356
00:20:56,760 --> 00:20:57,880
Back in a mo.

357
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:00,720
Are you all right?

358
00:21:01,280 --> 00:21:02,760
Totally. Peachy keen.

359
00:21:02,840 --> 00:21:05,400
Okay, then. Well, don't press
any buttons or pull any levers

360
00:21:05,480 --> 00:21:07,800
or make any funny faces.
Actually, don't move.

361
00:21:08,080 --> 00:21:10,280
Stand completely still. Don't breathe.

362
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:12,640
Well, you can breathe.

363
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:14,760
But shallow breaths.

364
00:21:35,600 --> 00:21:37,480
(SIGHING IN RELIEF)

365
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:40,560
What's wrong?

366
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:44,560
Did the Tardis say something to you?
Are you being mean?

367
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:45,720
No, it's not that.

368
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:49,240
Have we just watched the entire
life cycle of Earth, birth to death?

369
00:21:50,320 --> 00:21:53,160
-Yes.
-And you're okay with that?

370
00:21:55,920 --> 00:21:57,520
Yes.

371
00:21:58,120 --> 00:21:59,960
How can you be?

372
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:05,480
The Tardis, she's time.
We... We're the vortex.

373
00:22:06,520 --> 00:22:07,560
And so on.

374
00:22:07,640 --> 00:22:09,600
-It's not what I mean.
-Okay.

375
00:22:10,360 --> 00:22:12,440
Some help. Context.

376
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:16,720
Cheat sheet. Something?

377
00:22:16,800 --> 00:22:19,760
I mean, one minute you're in 1974,
looking for ghosts,

378
00:22:19,840 --> 00:22:22,680
but all you have to do is open your eyes
and talk to whoever is standing there.

379
00:22:23,120 --> 00:22:24,760
To you, I haven't been born yet.

380
00:22:26,320 --> 00:22:28,880
And to you, I've been dead
a hundred billion years.

381
00:22:31,600 --> 00:22:34,520
Is my body out there somewhere,
in the ground?

382
00:22:36,360 --> 00:22:38,240
Yes, I suppose it is.

383
00:22:38,840 --> 00:22:42,040
But here we are, talking,
so I am a ghost.

384
00:22:43,480 --> 00:22:45,840
To you, I'm a ghost.

385
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:48,440
We're all ghosts to you.

386
00:22:48,840 --> 00:22:51,080
We must be nothing.

387
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:53,680
No. No.

388
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:56,160
You're not that.

389
00:22:56,240 --> 00:22:58,680
Then what are we?
What can we possibly be?

390
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:10,280
You are the only mystery worth solving.

391
00:23:18,720 --> 00:23:20,840
(WHOOSHING)

392
00:23:32,720 --> 00:23:34,480
(WIND HOWLING)

393
00:23:35,920 --> 00:23:37,720
What's wrong?

394
00:23:38,560 --> 00:23:41,360
I just saw something I wish I hadn't.

395
00:23:42,040 --> 00:23:43,840
What did you see?

396
00:23:44,560 --> 00:23:46,520
That everything ends.

397
00:23:47,640 --> 00:23:49,760
No, not everything.

398
00:23:50,240 --> 00:23:53,320
Not love. Not always.

399
00:23:54,560 --> 00:23:57,880
Right! Done! That's it, gather round,
gather around. Roll up! Roll up!

400
00:24:02,400 --> 00:24:04,200
The Gast of Caliburn House.

401
00:24:04,480 --> 00:24:07,800
Never changing,
trapped in a moment of fear and torment.

402
00:24:07,880 --> 00:24:09,600
But what if she's not?

403
00:24:10,920 --> 00:24:15,280
What if she's just trapped somewhere
time runs more slowly than it does here?

404
00:24:15,600 --> 00:24:19,040
What if a second to her
was 100,000 years to us?

405
00:24:19,120 --> 00:24:23,000
And what if somebody has a magic box,
a blue box probably,

406
00:24:23,080 --> 00:24:25,720
what if said somebody could
take a snapshot of her, say,

407
00:24:25,800 --> 00:24:27,280
every few million years?

408
00:24:32,600 --> 00:24:33,920
She's not a ghost.

409
00:24:34,960 --> 00:24:38,960
But she's definitely a lost soul.
Her name is Hila Tacorian.

410
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:41,640
She's a pioneer.

411
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:44,640
A time traveller, or at least
she will be in a few hundred years.

412
00:24:45,080 --> 00:24:46,880
Time travel is not possible.
The paradoxes...

413
00:24:46,960 --> 00:24:48,600
Resolve themselves, by and large.

414
00:24:48,760 --> 00:24:50,240
How long has she been alone?

415
00:24:50,320 --> 00:24:52,040
Well, time travel is a funny old thing.

416
00:24:52,120 --> 00:24:56,080
I mean, from her perspective,
she crash-landed three minutes ago.

417
00:24:56,160 --> 00:24:59,160
Crash-landed? Where?

418
00:24:59,640 --> 00:25:03,560
She's in a pocket universe,
a distorted echo of our own.

419
00:25:03,640 --> 00:25:05,880
They happen sometimes
but never last for long.

420
00:25:15,440 --> 00:25:19,560
Our universe. Hila Tacorian's here,
in a pocket universe.

421
00:25:19,840 --> 00:25:21,720
You're a lantern,

422
00:25:21,800 --> 00:25:23,320
shining across the dimensions,

423
00:25:23,400 --> 00:25:26,480
guiding her home,
back to the land of the living.

424
00:25:29,800 --> 00:25:33,040
-But what's she running from?
-(SNAPS) Well, that's the best bit.

425
00:25:33,120 --> 00:25:34,920
We don't know yet. Shall we see?

426
00:25:42,240 --> 00:25:44,080
Oh.

427
00:25:44,840 --> 00:25:46,040
What is that?

428
00:25:47,600 --> 00:25:48,840
I don't know.

429
00:25:50,640 --> 00:25:52,880
Still, not to worry.

430
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:54,360
So what do we do?

431
00:25:54,440 --> 00:25:55,600
Not we, you.

432
00:25:57,560 --> 00:26:00,520
You save Hila Tacorian
because you are Emma Grayling.

433
00:26:01,080 --> 00:26:04,480
You are the lantern. The rest of us
are just along for the ride, I'm afraid.

434
00:26:06,680 --> 00:26:10,840
We need some sturdy rope
and a blue crystal from Metebelis III,

435
00:26:10,920 --> 00:26:12,840
plus some Kendal Mint Cake.

436
00:26:26,920 --> 00:26:29,360
-Don't do it.
-I'm sorry?

437
00:26:29,440 --> 00:26:33,120
Nobody asked her to risk her life.
This woman, she doesn't deserve...

438
00:26:35,400 --> 00:26:38,320
Whoever she is, however brilliant,
however brave, she's not you.

439
00:26:38,400 --> 00:26:41,400
She is not worth risking a single hair
on your head, not to me!

440
00:26:47,240 --> 00:26:49,280
Tell me what I'm thinking.

441
00:26:50,840 --> 00:26:54,520
I can't. I don't have your gift.

442
00:26:55,840 --> 00:26:57,960
You don't need it.

443
00:26:58,960 --> 00:27:02,000
Just look at me and tell me.

444
00:27:09,080 --> 00:27:11,880
There you are. You read my mind.

445
00:27:15,480 --> 00:27:17,520
-Can't you just... You know.
-What?

446
00:27:18,320 --> 00:27:20,560
Fly the Tardis into a parallel universe.

447
00:27:20,640 --> 00:27:24,840
Ah, it's not a parallel universe,
it's a pocket universe.

448
00:27:24,920 --> 00:27:26,640
Plus, it is collapsing.

449
00:27:26,720 --> 00:27:29,360
I mean, the Tardis could
get in there, all right,

450
00:27:29,440 --> 00:27:32,600
but entropy would
bleed her power sources, you see,

451
00:27:32,680 --> 00:27:37,640
trap her there until the entire universe
decayed back into the quantum foam,

452
00:27:38,240 --> 00:27:41,800
which would take about three minutes,
give or take, you know.

453
00:27:43,240 --> 00:27:44,600
(ELECTRONIC HUMMING)

454
00:27:47,640 --> 00:27:48,760
What is that?

455
00:27:48,840 --> 00:27:50,840
Subset of the Eye of Harmony.

456
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:52,760
-I don't...
-Of course you don't.

457
00:27:52,840 --> 00:27:53,960
Bit weird if you did.
I barely do myself.

458
00:27:54,040 --> 00:27:55,960
Right, you, sit down.

459
00:27:56,040 --> 00:28:00,040
All the way from Metebelis III.

460
00:28:02,040 --> 00:28:05,320
-What does it do?
-It amplifies your natural abilities,

461
00:28:05,400 --> 00:28:08,200
like a microphone or a pooper-scooper.

462
00:28:08,280 --> 00:28:10,240
(CLOCKS TICKING)

463
00:28:10,320 --> 00:28:11,680
What exactly is this arrangement?

464
00:28:11,760 --> 00:28:13,080
A psycho-chronograph.

465
00:28:14,040 --> 00:28:17,200
Forgive me, but isn't it all
a little bit, well, make do and mend?

466
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:19,320
Non-psychic technology won't work
where I'm going.

467
00:28:19,400 --> 00:28:21,680
Listen, all I need to do
is dive into another dimension,

468
00:28:21,760 --> 00:28:23,600
find the time traveller,
help her escape the monster,

469
00:28:23,680 --> 00:28:26,640
get home before the entire dimension
collapses and Bob's your uncle.

470
00:28:26,720 --> 00:28:27,840
Doctor,

471
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:30,360
will it hurt?

472
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:32,080
No.

473
00:28:32,720 --> 00:28:34,680
Well, yes, probably. A bit.

474
00:28:34,760 --> 00:28:36,600
Well, quite a lot, I don't know.
It might be agony.

475
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:38,920
To be perfectly honest,
I'd be interested to find out.

476
00:28:40,280 --> 00:28:41,320
(GULPS)

477
00:28:47,720 --> 00:28:49,560
(BOTH EXHALING)

478
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:53,600
I'm talking to the lost soul
that abides in this place.

479
00:28:53,960 --> 00:28:55,040
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

480
00:28:58,920 --> 00:29:01,440
I'm speaking to Hila Tacorian.

481
00:29:11,960 --> 00:29:13,080
(GROANS)

482
00:29:15,880 --> 00:29:17,280
(ELECTRONIC PINGING)

483
00:29:28,640 --> 00:29:31,080
See? The Witch of the Well.

484
00:29:32,360 --> 00:29:33,760
It's a wormhole.

485
00:29:33,840 --> 00:29:37,360
A reality well.
A door to the echo universe.

486
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:38,560
Ready?

487
00:29:39,160 --> 00:29:40,280
Ready!

488
00:29:44,360 --> 00:29:45,720
(NECK CRACKING)

489
00:29:46,560 --> 00:29:47,640
Geronimo.

490
00:29:48,240 --> 00:29:49,280
(SCREAMS)

491
00:29:53,240 --> 00:29:54,320
(SCREAMING)

492
00:29:57,040 --> 00:29:58,080
Doctor!

493
00:30:00,240 --> 00:30:01,400
Whoa!

494
00:30:21,880 --> 00:30:23,840
Hila! Hila!

495
00:30:25,760 --> 00:30:27,080
Hila Tacorian!

496
00:30:27,280 --> 00:30:28,360
(RUSTLING)

497
00:30:31,920 --> 00:30:32,960
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

498
00:30:36,520 --> 00:30:38,120
(RUSTLING CONTINUES)

499
00:30:52,240 --> 00:30:53,320
One,

500
00:30:54,360 --> 00:30:55,400
two,

501
00:30:56,320 --> 00:30:57,440
three!

502
00:30:57,520 --> 00:30:59,760
HILA: Help me!

503
00:31:00,560 --> 00:31:02,880
Help!

504
00:31:05,520 --> 00:31:08,600
-(EXCLAIMS) Hila Tacorian, I presume?
-Who are you?

505
00:31:08,680 --> 00:31:10,280
Collapsing universe, you and me dead.

506
00:31:10,360 --> 00:31:12,640
Two minutes, no time
complete sentences. Abandon planet!

507
00:31:12,720 --> 00:31:14,600
Wait!

508
00:31:14,760 --> 00:31:16,880
There's something in the mist.

509
00:31:16,960 --> 00:31:19,400
Then, run. Run!

510
00:31:23,040 --> 00:31:24,080
(PANTING)

511
00:31:25,720 --> 00:31:26,880
EMMA: Doctor?

512
00:31:27,840 --> 00:31:28,880
Doctor!

513
00:31:29,640 --> 00:31:30,680
Come home!

514
00:31:31,440 --> 00:31:32,760
Doctor, come home!

515
00:31:32,840 --> 00:31:33,880
(GROWLING)

516
00:31:36,280 --> 00:31:40,920
Okay, not that way, which means...
Uh, probably...

517
00:31:42,760 --> 00:31:44,760
-What's wrong?
-You know that exit I mentioned?

518
00:31:44,840 --> 00:31:46,680
-Yeah.
-I seem to have misplaced it.

519
00:31:46,760 --> 00:31:48,200
(RUSTLING)

520
00:31:51,480 --> 00:31:53,160
(LOW GROWLING)

521
00:31:57,120 --> 00:31:58,600
-EMMA: Doctor!
-This way.

522
00:31:59,240 --> 00:32:00,320
Doctor!

523
00:32:01,640 --> 00:32:03,080
Come home!

524
00:32:07,040 --> 00:32:08,400
Doctor, we're here.

525
00:32:08,480 --> 00:32:09,520
-Whoa.
-What's that?

526
00:32:09,600 --> 00:32:11,600
DOCTOR: An echo house
in an echo universe.

527
00:32:11,680 --> 00:32:15,080
Clever psychic. That is just top-notch.

528
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:19,120
Doctor!

529
00:32:22,200 --> 00:32:23,360
(RUSTLING)

530
00:32:24,720 --> 00:32:25,760
Doctor!

531
00:32:31,920 --> 00:32:33,320
-(GROWLING)
-Shh!

532
00:32:33,400 --> 00:32:34,440
(RUSTLING)

533
00:32:34,520 --> 00:32:36,080
It's looking for the way in.

534
00:32:36,160 --> 00:32:37,240
(BANGING)

535
00:32:41,120 --> 00:32:42,920
(CRASHING)

536
00:32:43,760 --> 00:32:45,720
I'm not strong enough!

537
00:32:45,800 --> 00:32:47,400
Just a few more seconds!

538
00:32:47,480 --> 00:32:48,640
(SCREAMING)

539
00:32:56,160 --> 00:32:57,280
Grab the rope.

540
00:32:57,360 --> 00:32:59,320
Give it three tugs, quick as you like.

541
00:33:02,200 --> 00:33:04,240
-What about you?
-I'll be next.

542
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:07,240
(GRUNTING)

543
00:33:08,800 --> 00:33:09,960
(GASPS)

544
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:18,800
(GRUNTING)

545
00:33:26,480 --> 00:33:27,640
(BANGING)

546
00:33:27,720 --> 00:33:29,960
Oh, that's what that noise was. Lovely.

547
00:33:30,040 --> 00:33:31,160
(INHALES SHARPLY)

548
00:33:34,240 --> 00:33:35,320
No!

549
00:33:52,920 --> 00:33:54,600
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

550
00:33:55,440 --> 00:33:57,000
(CREATURE GROWLING)

551
00:33:59,280 --> 00:34:01,760
-Huh.
-(SNARLING)

552
00:34:06,960 --> 00:34:07,960
Oh, dear.

553
00:34:11,080 --> 00:34:12,480
Oh, dear.

554
00:34:17,280 --> 00:34:18,360
Where are you?

555
00:34:24,280 --> 00:34:25,440
(WHISPERS) Wake up!

556
00:34:25,520 --> 00:34:27,280
Wake up! Open the thing!

557
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:28,720
I'm sorry.

558
00:34:28,800 --> 00:34:30,840
Don't be sorry, don't be.
What you did...

559
00:34:30,920 --> 00:34:32,200
Wasn't enough. She needs to do it again.

560
00:34:32,280 --> 00:34:34,240
-She can't. Look at her!
-She has to!

561
00:34:39,520 --> 00:34:40,840
We can't leave him.

562
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:46,160
I know that you feel
that you can't do this, Emma,

563
00:34:46,240 --> 00:34:48,800
but look at that woman over there.

564
00:34:49,640 --> 00:34:52,920
You saved her. She's only here
because of your strength.

565
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:55,080
And so am I.

566
00:34:56,120 --> 00:34:57,240
(PANTING)

567
00:34:59,520 --> 00:35:00,600
(RATTLING)

568
00:35:00,680 --> 00:35:02,520
Oh, come on!

569
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:04,640
Oh, let me in, you grumpy old cow!

570
00:35:04,720 --> 00:35:06,680
(ELECTRONIC BUZZING)

571
00:35:06,760 --> 00:35:07,800
Whoa.

572
00:35:08,520 --> 00:35:10,360
Emma, I was as lost as her

573
00:35:11,120 --> 00:35:12,440
but being with you,

574
00:35:13,480 --> 00:35:16,280
you gave me a reason to be, Emma.

575
00:35:16,560 --> 00:35:19,520
You brought me back from the dead.

576
00:35:36,960 --> 00:35:39,360
-What's this now?
-The Tardis voice visual interface.

577
00:35:39,840 --> 00:35:42,320
I'm programmed to select the image
of a person you have seen.

578
00:35:42,600 --> 00:35:44,840
Of several billion such images
in my data banks,

579
00:35:44,920 --> 00:35:46,600
this one best meets the criterion.

580
00:35:46,680 --> 00:35:50,480
Oh! Oh, you are a cow. I knew it!
Whatever. You have to help The Doctor.

581
00:35:50,560 --> 00:35:53,560
-The Doctor is in the pocket universe.
-You can enter the pocket universe.

582
00:35:53,640 --> 00:35:55,800
The entropy would drain the energy
from my heart.

583
00:35:55,880 --> 00:35:58,440
In four seconds, I'll be stranded.
In 10, I'll be dead.

584
00:35:58,520 --> 00:36:01,240
You're talking but all I can hear is,
"Meh-meh-meh-meh-meh.”

585
00:36:01,320 --> 00:36:03,080
Come on, let's go!

586
00:36:04,120 --> 00:36:06,480
Hey, hey, hey!

587
00:36:06,840 --> 00:36:07,920
Doctor.

588
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:11,960
Can you hear me?

589
00:36:14,400 --> 00:36:15,520
Doctor!

590
00:36:17,200 --> 00:36:18,680
Oh, come on!

591
00:36:23,520 --> 00:36:26,400
Doctor, can you hear me?

592
00:36:36,240 --> 00:36:38,240
(SCREAMING)

593
00:36:39,520 --> 00:36:40,640
Doctor!

594
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:44,360
Doctor, we're here.

595
00:36:44,440 --> 00:36:45,560
Come home!

596
00:36:46,480 --> 00:36:47,920
Emma?

597
00:36:51,680 --> 00:36:52,800
(CREATURE SNARLS)

598
00:36:53,160 --> 00:36:54,880
(GROWLING)

599
00:36:56,880 --> 00:36:59,320
What do you want?

600
00:36:59,520 --> 00:37:01,040
To frighten me I suppose, hey?

601
00:37:01,440 --> 00:37:02,520
(LAUGHING EVILLY)

602
00:37:02,600 --> 00:37:05,120
'Cause that's what you do, you hide.

603
00:37:05,920 --> 00:37:08,120
You're the bogeyman under the bed,

604
00:37:08,960 --> 00:37:11,000
seeking whom you may devour.

605
00:37:17,560 --> 00:37:19,120
(GASPING)

606
00:37:20,360 --> 00:37:21,960
(LAUGHING EVILLY)

607
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:26,200
You want me to be afraid.

608
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:27,880
And well done.

609
00:37:29,040 --> 00:37:30,600
I am The Doctor

610
00:37:32,360 --> 00:37:33,560
and I am afraid.

611
00:37:34,560 --> 00:37:36,280
(LAUGHING EVILLY)

612
00:37:37,840 --> 00:37:39,160
(CLARA SCREAMING)

613
00:37:40,480 --> 00:37:41,760
(EXCLAIMING)

614
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:45,600
EMMA: Doctor!

615
00:37:46,760 --> 00:37:48,480
Hurry!

616
00:37:50,880 --> 00:37:52,800
(CREATURE SNARLS, DOCTOR GASPS)

617
00:37:52,880 --> 00:37:54,560
(LAUGHING EVILLY)

618
00:37:57,760 --> 00:38:00,320
So why am I still here, huh?

619
00:38:00,720 --> 00:38:03,240
Why not just eat me?

620
00:38:04,720 --> 00:38:06,400
Huh?

621
00:38:06,680 --> 00:38:07,920
Come on.

622
00:38:10,160 --> 00:38:12,920
-Because you still need me.
-(GROWLING)

623
00:38:13,920 --> 00:38:17,160
Yeah, you need me
to piggyback you across. (LAUGHS)

624
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:22,120
Ah. To which I say...

625
00:38:24,240 --> 00:38:25,800
Come on, then, big boy.

626
00:38:27,600 --> 00:38:28,720
Chase me.

627
00:38:33,560 --> 00:38:35,240
(GROWLING)

628
00:38:37,360 --> 00:38:38,720
(GROWLING)

629
00:38:38,800 --> 00:38:39,960
(GROANING)

630
00:38:43,840 --> 00:38:45,000
(CLARA SCREAMING)

631
00:38:46,960 --> 00:38:48,040
(LAUGHS)

632
00:38:48,520 --> 00:38:49,960
(WHOOPING)

633
00:38:50,040 --> 00:38:51,120
(GRUNTING)

634
00:39:00,440 --> 00:39:02,960
(SCREAMING)

635
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:09,920
(EMMA SOBBING)

636
00:39:11,440 --> 00:39:12,880
(WHISTLES IN RELIEF)

637
00:39:14,920 --> 00:39:16,040
(GROANING)

638
00:39:20,120 --> 00:39:22,480
It's over. (LAUGHING)

639
00:39:37,840 --> 00:39:39,840
You wanted a word?

640
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:42,360
-Well, if that's...
-That's fine.

641
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:47,040
You didn't come here
for the ghost, did you?

642
00:39:47,120 --> 00:39:48,320
No.

643
00:39:48,400 --> 00:39:50,480
-You came here for me.
-Yes.

644
00:39:50,560 --> 00:39:52,400
-Why?
-I needed to ask you something.

645
00:39:52,520 --> 00:39:54,480
-Then ask.
-Clara.

646
00:39:54,560 --> 00:39:55,640
Yes?

647
00:39:59,320 --> 00:40:01,160
-What is she?
-She's a girl.

648
00:40:01,240 --> 00:40:04,160
Yes, but what kind of girl,
specifically?

649
00:40:04,800 --> 00:40:07,720
She's a perfectly ordinary girl.

650
00:40:08,280 --> 00:40:09,880
-Very pretty.
-Mmm.

651
00:40:09,960 --> 00:40:11,200
-Very clever.
-Mmm.

652
00:40:12,600 --> 00:40:15,120
More scared than she lets on.

653
00:40:16,040 --> 00:40:19,080
-And that's it, is it?
-Why? Is that not enough?

654
00:40:28,360 --> 00:40:29,560
(DOCTOR SIGHS)

655
00:40:31,080 --> 00:40:32,240
Where will you go?

656
00:40:32,320 --> 00:40:35,640
He can't take me home.
History says I went missing.

657
00:40:35,720 --> 00:40:36,800
But he can change history.

658
00:40:36,880 --> 00:40:39,760
No. No, no. I can't, actually.
There are fixed points in time, you see.

659
00:40:39,840 --> 00:40:41,560
-(CLEARS THROAT) Hi.
-What?

660
00:40:44,600 --> 00:40:46,600
I knew you were there.

661
00:40:46,880 --> 00:40:49,480
-I could feel you.
-I know.

662
00:40:51,960 --> 00:40:54,240
-Have we...
-We can't have.

663
00:40:54,320 --> 00:40:58,040
-You haven't even been born yet.
-No, you can't have met but she can be

664
00:40:58,120 --> 00:41:02,480
your great-great-great-great-great-
granddaughter.

665
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:06,400
Eh? Yours, too, of course. But you
guessed that already, didn't you?

666
00:41:08,360 --> 00:41:11,000
Oh. Apparently not.

667
00:41:11,520 --> 00:41:13,840
-The paradoxes...
-Resolve themselves, by and large.

668
00:41:13,920 --> 00:41:16,720
That's why the psychic link
was so powerful,

669
00:41:16,800 --> 00:41:20,440
blood calling to blood, out of time.

670
00:41:20,520 --> 00:41:23,360
Not everything ends, eh?
Not love. Not always.

671
00:41:23,640 --> 00:41:27,400
Doctor, what about, um...
(CLEARS THROAT) What about us?

672
00:41:27,480 --> 00:41:28,960
Emma and me?

673
00:41:29,400 --> 00:41:31,280
-What about you?
-Well,

674
00:41:31,360 --> 00:41:34,720
what's supposed to happen?
I mean, what do we do now?

675
00:41:34,800 --> 00:41:36,600
Hold hands.

676
00:41:36,680 --> 00:41:40,160
That's what you're meant to do.
Keep doing that and don't let go.

677
00:41:40,240 --> 00:41:42,520
That's the secret.

678
00:41:45,440 --> 00:41:48,280
CLARA: Doctor! I'm not happy.

679
00:41:49,360 --> 00:41:51,360
Yeah, you need me
to piggyback you across.

680
00:41:51,680 --> 00:41:52,720
I'm not holding your hand.

681
00:41:52,800 --> 00:41:53,920
(SNARLING)

682
00:41:54,680 --> 00:41:58,480
Oh, I'm so slow!
I am slow. I'm notorious for it.

683
00:41:58,560 --> 00:42:02,000
That's always been my problem, but...
but I get there in the end. Oh, yes.

684
00:42:02,080 --> 00:42:03,600
-Doctor?
-How do sharks make babies?

685
00:42:04,560 --> 00:42:06,640
-Carefully.
-No. No, no, no. Happily.

686
00:42:07,400 --> 00:42:08,480
Sharks don't actually smile.

687
00:42:08,560 --> 00:42:11,200
They just, well... They've got lots
and lots of teeth. They're quite eaty.

688
00:42:11,280 --> 00:42:15,560
Exactly. But birds do it, bees do it,
even educated fleas do it.

689
00:42:15,920 --> 00:42:19,080
Every lonely monster needs a companion.

690
00:42:20,600 --> 00:42:23,240
-There's two of them!
-(DOCTOR LAUGHING)

691
00:42:23,320 --> 00:42:26,920
You know, it's the oldest story
in the universe, this one or any other.

692
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:28,800
Boy and girl fall in love, get separated

693
00:42:28,880 --> 00:42:31,680
by events, war, politics,
accidents in time.

694
00:42:31,760 --> 00:42:35,640
She's thrown out of the hex,
or he's thrown into it.

695
00:42:35,720 --> 00:42:37,400
Since then they've been yearning
for each other

696
00:42:37,480 --> 00:42:40,400
across time and space,
across dimensions.

697
00:42:40,480 --> 00:42:44,200
This isn't a ghost story,
it's a love story.

698
00:42:47,880 --> 00:42:49,000
Sorry.

699
00:42:50,280 --> 00:42:51,720
Excuse me. Excuse me.

700
00:42:51,920 --> 00:42:53,000
Sorry to interrupt
the rest of your life.

701
00:42:53,080 --> 00:42:56,360
So, tiny favour to ask.

702
00:43:02,120 --> 00:43:04,800
I'm sorry! I understand now!

703
00:43:04,880 --> 00:43:07,360
-(GROWLING)
-I can take you to her.

704
00:43:08,480 --> 00:43:11,160
I can take you to a safe place,
far away from here.

705
00:43:11,880 --> 00:43:13,680
You can be together!

706
00:43:13,760 --> 00:43:14,840
(EXCLAIMS)

707
00:43:15,320 --> 00:43:17,600
Well, come on, then. She's waiting.

708
00:43:17,920 --> 00:43:19,080
(GROWLING)

709
00:43:26,840 --> 00:43:31,240
Well, hello again, you old Romeo, you.

710
00:43:31,320 --> 00:43:33,760
-(WHOOSHING)
-Now, here she comes.

711
00:43:34,520 --> 00:43:36,040
CLARA: Ha-ha! (WHOOPS)

712
00:43:36,520 --> 00:43:38,160
(YELLING)

713
00:43:39,240 --> 00:43:40,680
(CLARA WHOOPING)

714
00:43:40,760 --> 00:43:42,720
Get ready to jump.

715
00:43:48,320 --> 00:43:50,840
Running away with a spaceman in a box,
anything could happen to you.

716
00:43:50,920 --> 00:43:52,080
Whoa!

717
00:43:52,360 --> 00:43:54,280
It's good salvage. I can smell it.

718
00:43:54,640 --> 00:43:55,760
Clara. Where is she?

719
00:43:55,840 --> 00:43:57,280
She's still onboard.

720
00:43:57,360 --> 00:43:59,280
If you help me get her out,
you get the machine.

721
00:43:59,360 --> 00:44:01,440
The salvage of a lifetime.

722
00:44:02,160 --> 00:44:03,600
MAN: Multiple life forms
onboard the Tardis.

723
00:44:03,680 --> 00:44:04,840
What do you keep in here?

724
00:44:04,920 --> 00:44:07,080
What are you, eh? A trick? A trap?

725
00:44:07,160 --> 00:44:09,880
We do what we came for,
tear this ship apart.

726
00:44:09,960 --> 00:44:11,880
If we're going to die here,
you're going to tell me what they are.

727
00:44:11,960 --> 00:44:13,160
-(GROWL)
-I can't.

728
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:16,320
-Where are we going?
-The centre of the Tardis.

